WEBVTT

00:01.700 --> 00:04.700
<i>[jazz music]</i>

00:04.700 --> 00:11.700
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:18.430 --> 00:21.400
[cheers and applause]

00:21.400 --> 00:23.000
<i>- From the Penn & Teller Theater</i>

00:23.000 --> 00:24.970
<i>at the Rio Hotel in Las Vegas,</i>

00:24.970 --> 00:26.330
<i>here's our host:</i>

00:26.330 --> 00:30.300
<i>Alyson Hannigan!</i>

00:30.300 --> 00:33.300
[cheers and applause]

00:41.570 --> 00:43.470
- Welcome to "Fool Us."

00:43.470 --> 00:46.130
What's harder than fooling
Penn and Teller once?

00:46.130 --> 00:47.630
Fooling them twice.

00:47.630 --> 00:49.700
Tonight, we're gonna make
"Fool Us" history

00:49.700 --> 00:51.570
because each
and every performer

00:51.570 --> 00:54.100
has already baffled
our dynamic duo

00:54.100 --> 00:56.070
and they're back
with brand-new tricks,

00:56.070 --> 00:58.170
hoping for the same result.

00:58.170 --> 01:00.070
Will history repeat itself?

01:00.070 --> 01:02.630
Or will Penn and Teller
be redeemed?

01:02.630 --> 01:04.670
Let the rematch begin.

01:04.670 --> 01:06.000
First, in this corner,

01:06.000 --> 01:08.130
the tag-team champions of magic:

01:08.130 --> 01:10.470
here are Penn and Teller!

01:10.470 --> 01:13.470
[cheers and applause]

01:13.470 --> 01:20.630
♪ ♪

01:20.630 --> 01:24.300
Mwuah.
Yes.

01:24.300 --> 01:26.070
Whoo!

01:28.270 --> 01:30.670
- Hello.

01:30.670 --> 01:33.300
- Of course, tonight's
first rematch magician

01:33.300 --> 01:36.100
has already won a spot
in Penn and Teller's show,

01:36.100 --> 01:38.700
but he's looking to book
a return engagement.

01:38.700 --> 01:40.670
Let's re-meet him now.

01:42.430 --> 01:44.030
<i>- Fooling Penn and Teller
was awesome.</i>

01:44.030 --> 01:45.700
<i>You can tell
how excited I was</i>

01:45.700 --> 01:47.070
<i>if you watch the tape.</i>

01:47.070 --> 01:49.270
[cheers and applause]
- Fooler!

01:49.270 --> 01:52.570
- The joy that moment gave me
is--

01:52.570 --> 01:54.870
<i>is right up there
with anything else</i>

01:54.870 --> 01:56.830
that has happened positively
in my life.

01:56.830 --> 01:59.330
<i>The thing is,
I fooled them naked.</i>

01:59.330 --> 02:00.930
- Okay. Whoo!
Oh!

02:00.930 --> 02:03.230
- I didn't really know
that it would become my thing.

02:03.230 --> 02:04.970
<i>All the people
that saw that show</i>

02:04.970 --> 02:08.130
<i>expect to see me naked,
all the time.</i>

02:08.130 --> 02:11.370
I just can't seem to
break free of people calling me

02:11.370 --> 02:12.730
<i>"The Naked Magician,"
or saying</i>

02:12.730 --> 02:14.630
"Oh, it's nice to see you
with clothes on."

02:14.630 --> 02:16.530
- It's okay to perform naked.

02:16.530 --> 02:19.800
Junior's always naked.
Benson is always naked.

02:19.800 --> 02:21.830
- Man, I want
to put my clothes on.

02:21.830 --> 02:25.530
[cheers and applause]

02:25.530 --> 02:29.070
- Please welcome back
Vinny Grosso!

02:29.070 --> 02:31.530
[cheers and applause]

02:34.400 --> 02:36.070
- Thank you.

02:36.070 --> 02:39.470
The last time I performed,
I had to use a privacy screen.

02:39.470 --> 02:43.170
That won't be necessary
this time.

02:43.700 --> 02:46.830
[applause]

02:50.000 --> 02:52.670
One of my favorite
Penn and Teller routines

02:52.670 --> 02:54.730
uses a psychic gorilla.

02:54.730 --> 02:57.270
I heard a rumor
that Penn and Teller

02:57.270 --> 02:59.630
have another
psychic animal trick

02:59.630 --> 03:01.570
in their warehouse,

03:01.570 --> 03:03.030
one that they've never performed,

03:03.030 --> 03:05.330
and I don't even think
they remember.

03:05.330 --> 03:07.370
I asked
a close, personal friend

03:07.370 --> 03:10.900
of Penn and Teller
to sneak in and steal it.

03:10.900 --> 03:13.330
I mean, how cool would it be
to fool Penn and Teller

03:13.330 --> 03:14.670
with their own trick?

03:14.670 --> 03:17.370
[laughter]
So he agreed.

03:17.370 --> 03:19.830
He got it, and, uh,
he's willing

03:19.830 --> 03:22.700
to talk me through the trick
via video conference

03:22.700 --> 03:25.130
just as long
as I hide his identity.

03:25.130 --> 03:27.000
So, if we can
try and connect

03:27.000 --> 03:30.200
with the mysterious friend
of Penn and Teller...

03:30.200 --> 03:32.230
<i>[Gilbert Gottfried]
- All right, so I stand here</i>

03:32.230 --> 03:34.070
<i>and my--</i>
- [laughing]

03:34.070 --> 03:36.370
<i>- My--my identity's hidden,
right?</i>

03:36.370 --> 03:38.670
<i>It's hidden.
No one knows who I am.</i>

03:38.670 --> 03:40.830
- No one can see you.
<i>- Good, good.</i>

03:40.830 --> 03:43.300
<i>Yeah, you blurred me out--
All right.</i>

03:43.300 --> 03:45.630
- Yeah.
<i>- I stole this trick...</i>

03:45.630 --> 03:47.630
- [laughing]
<i>- From Penn and Teller.</i>

03:47.630 --> 03:51.270
<i>- And, uh-- 'cause they've
got lousy security.</i>

03:51.270 --> 03:53.200
<i>They're idiots,
and they've got</i>

03:53.200 --> 03:54.670
<i>lousy secu--</i>

03:54.670 --> 03:57.070
<i>Well, even if they had
good security</i>

03:57.070 --> 04:00.070
<i>they'd still be idiots,
but it would be</i>

04:00.070 --> 04:02.500
<i>too lengthy to talk about.</i>

04:02.500 --> 04:05.230
[laughter]
<i>Here, first let's, uh,</i>

04:05.230 --> 04:08.000
<i>look at the instructions,
here.</i>

04:08.000 --> 04:13.400
<i>"Get a random volunteer
from the audience."</i>

04:13.400 --> 04:18.029
<i>This may take a while,
so I'll take a break.</i>

04:18.029 --> 04:20.200
- Whoa, whoa, whoa, stop.
[laughter]

04:20.200 --> 04:22.200
Eh, forget it, forget it,
forget it.

04:22.200 --> 04:25.200
[laughter and applause]

04:27.170 --> 04:28.800
I--I think
we can remove the blur,

04:28.800 --> 04:31.200
and everyone knows
it's Gilbert Gottfried.

04:31.200 --> 04:34.230
[cheers and applause]

04:34.930 --> 04:38.400
Teller, in your drawer over
there, there's a--a foam ball.

04:38.400 --> 04:39.830
If you could take that out

04:39.830 --> 04:44.330
and, uh, give it a toss
randomly into the audience?

04:44.330 --> 04:47.130
We'll try and find
a volunteer.

04:47.130 --> 04:49.570
What is your name?
- Mark.

04:49.570 --> 04:51.530
- Mark. Let's give Mark
a nice round of applause.

04:51.530 --> 04:53.230
Come on up, Mark.

04:53.230 --> 04:54.970
[cheers and applause]

04:57.800 --> 04:59.100
Thank you, Mark.
Nice you meet you.

04:59.100 --> 05:00.170
- You, too.
- We're gonna walk

05:00.170 --> 05:01.730
right over here,
and, uh,

05:01.730 --> 05:03.270
hopefully we can call
Gilbert back

05:03.270 --> 05:04.930
now that we have a volunteer.

05:05.930 --> 05:07.870
- Okay, perfect.

05:07.870 --> 05:12.970
"Now go through the, uh,
animals with the audience."

05:12.970 --> 05:15.830
Uh, okay, so,
we've got a turtle.

05:15.830 --> 05:18.670
Uh, we have a raccoon.

05:18.670 --> 05:21.430
Uh, we have a penguin.

05:21.430 --> 05:22.970
<i>An elephant.</i>

05:22.970 --> 05:25.130
<i>And, uh, this--</i>

05:25.130 --> 05:28.230
this was left over
by those other two--

05:28.230 --> 05:30.530
- [laughing]
<i>- Vegas, it's a tiger.</i>

05:30.530 --> 05:32.570
- You mean Siegfried and Roy.
[laughter]

05:32.570 --> 05:34.470
<i>- Yeah, Siegfried and Roy.</i>
- Yes.

05:34.470 --> 05:36.030
[laughter]
<i>Okay.</i>

05:36.030 --> 05:40.430
<i>And now-- oh, there's--
there's one more here.</i>

05:40.430 --> 05:43.170
<i>And that is my favorite...</i>

05:43.170 --> 05:44.170
- [laughing]

05:44.170 --> 05:45.470
<i>- A parrot.</i>
- Of course.

05:45.470 --> 05:49.830
- Now we gotta have
the volunteer look away...

05:49.830 --> 05:50.970
- So, if you'd just
cover yours eyes.

05:50.970 --> 05:53.570
<i>- While I make a prediction.</i>

05:53.570 --> 05:57.470
And I can seal
the prediction with--

05:57.470 --> 05:58.930
<i>with this envelope.</i>

05:58.930 --> 06:00.200
<i>See, that's...</i>

06:00.200 --> 06:03.730
- Perfect.
<i>- Very well concealed now.</i>

06:03.730 --> 06:06.100
Now, uh--uh--

06:06.100 --> 06:07.700
uh, Vinny?

06:07.700 --> 06:11.930
You take the duplicate box
of animals

06:11.930 --> 06:13.870
<i>that I sent you,</i>

06:13.870 --> 06:17.000
<i>and--and you show them
to the audience.</i>

06:17.000 --> 06:18.800
- I have a turtle...
<i>- Yeah?</i>

06:18.800 --> 06:20.200
- An elephant...
<i>- Perfect.</i>

06:20.200 --> 06:22.000
- The spider...
<i>- That's good.</i>

06:22.000 --> 06:23.600
- The, uh, tiger.
<i>- Yes.</i>

06:23.600 --> 06:26.130
- And the parrot, yeah.
<i>- Yes, excellent.</i>

06:26.130 --> 06:29.430
<i>Okay, now have your friend...</i>
- That's you, Mark.

06:29.430 --> 06:31.500
<i>- Close his eyes...</i>
- So, close your eyes...

06:31.500 --> 06:32.670
<i>- Reach into the box...</i>

06:32.670 --> 06:33.870
- And I need you to
reach into the box...

06:33.870 --> 06:35.370
<i>- And remove
the stuffed animal.</i>

06:35.370 --> 06:36.430
- And grab an animal.

06:36.430 --> 06:38.930
There you go.
[gasps, amazement]

06:38.930 --> 06:41.130
Oh, it's--
<i>- What--what's that?</i>

06:41.130 --> 06:44.870
- It--It's a gorilla.
<i>- What? It--it's a...</i>

06:44.870 --> 06:46.100
<i>[stammering]</i>
- Was this--

06:46.100 --> 06:47.500
Did you guys do this?

06:47.500 --> 06:49.930
<i>- What--what--
what's going on, here?</i>

06:49.930 --> 06:51.500
- I--I think Penn and Teller--
<i>- That's not--</i>

06:51.500 --> 06:53.230
<i>That's not--
How's that--</i>

06:53.230 --> 06:54.770
- No, no it isn't the parrot.
<i>- Yeah, you had a--</i>

06:54.770 --> 06:57.230
- I think they did it.
<i>- You had a box of parrots!</i>

06:57.230 --> 06:59.830
- It--it is a box of parrots.
<i>- A box of parrots.</i>

06:59.830 --> 07:03.200
How could you possibly
screw this one up?

07:03.200 --> 07:04.630
<i>- No, no--
[laughter]</i>

07:04.630 --> 07:07.770
- There's no way!
There's no way!

07:07.770 --> 07:10.270
<i>How could you be that stupid--</i>
- No, I got it--

07:10.270 --> 07:12.030
I think I--Gilbert.

07:12.030 --> 07:14.370
The--the
prediction is concealed

07:14.370 --> 07:15.770
inside the envelope.

07:15.770 --> 07:17.970
It said inside,
not by the envelope.

07:17.970 --> 07:20.000
<i>- Oh, in the envelope.</i>
- Yeah.

07:20.000 --> 07:23.000
Mark's prediction should be...

07:27.270 --> 07:29.070
- Mark, is that
your prediction?

07:29.070 --> 07:30.430
- Yes.
- Yes.

07:30.430 --> 07:32.070
Give Mark a nice round
of applause for helping me,

07:32.070 --> 07:33.530
and Gilbert Gottfried as well.

07:33.530 --> 07:34.900
Thank you, sir.
[cheers and applause]

07:34.900 --> 07:37.570
- Vinny Grosso!

07:37.570 --> 07:41.070
[happy exclamation]
- Thank you. Thank you.

07:41.730 --> 07:44.230
- So, does it feel different
to have clothes on?

07:44.230 --> 07:46.100
- So much different.
- Yeah?

07:46.100 --> 07:47.670
- [laughing] Yes.
- You like it?

07:47.670 --> 07:49.170
- Um, I think that that
this is gonna work for me.

07:49.170 --> 07:50.170
- I think it works.

07:50.170 --> 07:51.230
- I think this will be
my new thing.

07:51.230 --> 07:52.730
- So the first time
you fooled them,

07:52.730 --> 07:54.970
you didn't realize
you fooled them.

07:54.970 --> 07:56.970
- No, no I--I didn't.

07:56.970 --> 07:58.930
Being naked
and onstage, up here,

07:58.930 --> 08:00.530
it's a--
first of all, this whole thing

08:00.530 --> 08:02.400
becomes a blur, but

08:02.400 --> 08:04.330
when Penn started talking
to me,

08:04.330 --> 08:07.100
I had really no idea
what he was talking about,

08:07.100 --> 08:10.030
and I just assumed that--
that it was--

08:10.030 --> 08:12.130
he was telling me how--
how the trick was done.

08:12.130 --> 08:14.730
So when he said,
"You fooled us,"

08:14.730 --> 08:17.630
it was as genuine of a response
as you can get.

08:17.630 --> 08:19.230
- Yeah.
So is there a lot

08:19.230 --> 08:21.330
riding on whether or not
you're fooling them?

08:21.330 --> 08:23.200
'Cause you already have
one trophy.

08:23.200 --> 08:24.700
- Certainly fooling them
would be great,

08:24.700 --> 08:27.030
but, man, I didn't think
I could do it the first time.

08:27.030 --> 08:29.070
And I--
this is probably

08:29.070 --> 08:31.500
a longer shot
than the first one.

08:31.500 --> 08:32.630
- All right.

08:32.630 --> 08:34.130
Well, let's see
if Penn and Teller

08:34.130 --> 08:36.270
can expose your trick.
- Okay.

08:36.270 --> 08:39.200
- So first of all,
can we examine that box?

08:39.200 --> 08:41.100
- Uh, yeah, there--
there are a lot of

08:41.100 --> 08:42.600
tricky boxes in Las Vegas.

08:42.600 --> 08:44.300
- No, we can't examine the box.
- This is not one of them.

08:44.300 --> 08:46.330
- You're not gonna let us
examine the box.

08:46.330 --> 08:47.330
- Oop.

08:51.970 --> 08:55.270
- Okay. Okay.
[laughter]

08:55.270 --> 08:57.870
That was not part
of what we were busting you on.

08:57.870 --> 08:59.670
No, no,
we had the other part.

08:59.670 --> 09:02.370
We think that when Gilbert
was holding up

09:02.370 --> 09:04.670
that piece of paper--
which is amazing,

09:04.670 --> 09:06.270
Gilbert's barely a monkey.
[laughter]

09:06.270 --> 09:08.370
Getting him to even hold up
a piece of paper

09:08.370 --> 09:09.570
is remarkable.

09:09.570 --> 09:10.830
He can't do anything.

09:10.830 --> 09:12.630
He certainly can't fool us.

09:12.630 --> 09:14.430
He held up a piece of paper
that was

09:14.430 --> 09:16.530
blue screen, green screen,
chroma key,

09:16.530 --> 09:19.270
and you had one
of your little minions--

09:19.270 --> 09:21.100
out in the booth,
out in the truck--

09:21.100 --> 09:23.630
that laid in the name Mark,
didn't you?

09:23.630 --> 09:24.930
- Um...

09:24.930 --> 09:27.070
- He was holding up
a blue card.

09:27.070 --> 09:28.770
- Was it a visual effect?
- No. No.

09:28.770 --> 09:29.970
- It wasn't exactly
how you described it.

09:29.970 --> 09:31.030
- See, this is the, uh...
- Ohh.

09:31.030 --> 09:32.370
- Problem you have here.

09:32.370 --> 09:34.930
If there's one thing we hate,
it's being fooled.

09:34.930 --> 09:37.700
If there's two things we hate,
it's being fooled twice

09:37.700 --> 09:39.100
by the same guy.

09:39.100 --> 09:40.630
If there's three things
we hate,

09:40.630 --> 09:43.870
it's being fooled
by Gilbert Gottfried.

09:43.870 --> 09:44.970
[laughter]

09:44.970 --> 09:46.600
Now I'm telling you
right now, Vinny,

09:46.600 --> 09:50.470
we will not be fooled
by Gilbert Gottfried.

09:50.470 --> 09:51.970
[laughter]
What I'm trying to say to you,

09:51.970 --> 09:54.100
Vinny, you idiot,
is you fooled us.

09:54.100 --> 09:56.330
- Whoa!
[cheering and applause]

09:56.330 --> 09:58.670
- That's what
I'm trying to tell you.

09:58.670 --> 10:00.000
But I want you to swear--

10:00.000 --> 10:03.000
Wait.
Stop! Stop!

10:03.000 --> 10:04.970
Stop, don't give that to him.

10:04.970 --> 10:07.230
I want your word of honor...
- Yes.

10:07.230 --> 10:09.470
- Gilbert Gottfried,
that piece of [bleep],

10:09.470 --> 10:11.730
did not fool us, okay?
- Yes.

10:11.730 --> 10:13.700
- He did not fool us;
Vinny did.

10:13.700 --> 10:15.500
But not Gilbert.
[laughter]

10:15.500 --> 10:18.500
Not Gilbert, Vinny.
- Vinny Grosso

10:18.500 --> 10:22.870
fooled Penn and Teller
a second time!

10:22.870 --> 10:25.430
Congratulations.

10:25.430 --> 10:27.230
[happy sigh]

10:27.230 --> 10:28.600
Not Gilbert.
- Not Gilbert.

10:28.600 --> 10:30.500
- No. We--
- Not Gilbert.

10:30.500 --> 10:32.400
- We've got a fooler
in the house.

10:32.400 --> 10:34.330
- But not Gilbert.
- Not Gilbert.

10:34.330 --> 10:35.600
- We'll see--
- Not Gilbert.

10:35.600 --> 10:36.970
- We'll see
if we can find another...

10:36.970 --> 10:38.570
- It wasn't Gilbert Gottfried!
- When we come back.

10:38.570 --> 10:40.270
- Gilbert Gottfried
will not fool me!

10:40.270 --> 10:41.930
Never! Never!

10:41.930 --> 10:44.570
<i>[jazz music]</i>

10:47.130 --> 10:49.700
<i>[jazz music]</i>

10:49.700 --> 10:52.470
[cheering and applause]

10:52.470 --> 10:54.330
- Welcome back to "Fool Us."

10:54.330 --> 10:56.670
The British are coming.
The British are coming.

10:56.670 --> 10:58.400
Really.
Take a look.

11:00.500 --> 11:03.000
- Hello, I am Rhys Morgan.
- I am Robert West.

11:03.000 --> 11:04.700
And we are...

11:04.700 --> 11:06.970
[together]
Time-travelling magicians.

11:06.970 --> 11:09.570
- And we fooled Penn and Teller
back in the very first season

11:09.570 --> 11:10.970
of this show.
- Ooh.

11:10.970 --> 11:12.470
Why don't we travel
back in time

11:12.470 --> 11:14.030
to show everybody?
- Ooh.

11:14.030 --> 11:15.370
[together]
Here we go.

11:15.370 --> 11:17.470
[device beeps]
[pop]

11:17.470 --> 11:19.800
- Like every other magician
on the show...

11:19.800 --> 11:22.870
- We awaited their decision
with bated breath.

11:22.870 --> 11:25.570
[both chattering indistinctly]

11:25.570 --> 11:27.400
- There we are.

11:27.400 --> 11:29.270
- What do you mean?
- That's empty. This is empty.

11:29.270 --> 11:33.600
- It's empty.
- There was no deck switch.

11:33.600 --> 11:35.670
- You fooled us.
- Yeah!

11:35.670 --> 11:36.700
[cheers and applause]

11:36.700 --> 11:37.870
- Well played, old chap.

11:37.870 --> 11:39.770
- Thank you.

11:41.130 --> 11:42.330
<i>- When we fooled
Penn and Teller,</i>

11:42.330 --> 11:43.700
<i>we weren't really
expecting it.</i>

11:43.700 --> 11:45.330
It helped enormously.
- Helped us leave our jobs.

11:45.330 --> 11:47.130
- It helped us leave our jobs,
and it helped us sort of

11:47.130 --> 11:48.330
just get going, really.

11:48.330 --> 11:50.470
- Will we fool
Penn and Teller again?

11:50.470 --> 11:52.730
- Well, we are time travelers,
so we do know.

11:52.730 --> 11:54.700
- Well, yes, we know,
but they do not.

11:54.700 --> 11:56.500
- Oh, good point.

11:56.500 --> 11:58.100
Let's find out.

11:58.100 --> 12:00.270
<i>[mysterious music]</i>

12:00.270 --> 12:03.070
[cheers and applause]

12:03.070 --> 12:07.800
- From across the pond,
here are Morgan and West.

12:07.800 --> 12:09.600
[cheering and applause]

12:09.600 --> 12:11.270
- Hello, good evening.

12:11.270 --> 12:12.730
Good evening, everybody.

12:12.730 --> 12:14.630
My name is Rhys Morgan.
- And I'm Robert West.

12:14.630 --> 12:16.400
