38:52.500 --> 38:54.700
has been used more and more
by laypeople.

38:54.700 --> 38:56.530
People that aren't in
the magic community

38:56.530 --> 38:58.300
use the word "misdirection."

38:58.300 --> 39:01.430
If you read editorials,
or a pundit speaking,

39:01.430 --> 39:03.470
they'll say
"misdirection" a lot.

39:03.470 --> 39:06.470
And the way laypeople use it
is wrong--well, not wrong.

39:06.470 --> 39:08.630
You can't really
use words wrong.

39:08.630 --> 39:10.230
They grow, they change.

39:10.230 --> 39:12.830
But less nuanced
than magicians use it.

39:12.830 --> 39:14.630
When laypeople use
the word "misdirection,"

39:14.630 --> 39:17.630
they often mean it as a--
as a synonym for distraction.

39:17.630 --> 39:18.930
Like, "Hey!
Look over there!"

39:18.930 --> 39:20.800
I do something sneaky
over here.

39:20.800 --> 39:23.130
And then, when you come back,
the--the magic's done,

39:23.130 --> 39:26.900
and the problem with that is,
that doesn't work.

39:26.900 --> 39:29.130
If you know you're distracted
and look away,

39:29.130 --> 39:31.500
when you come back,
you aren't fooled at all.

39:31.500 --> 39:34.400
When magicians use the word
"misdirection,"

39:34.400 --> 39:35.630
it's more complicated.

39:35.630 --> 39:38.800
It's more kind of a--
a curating of attention.

39:38.800 --> 39:42.130
